article.description: Aiysha Smith scored a career-high 30 points and freshman Seimone Augustus added 20 as No. 4 LSU outlasted No. 17 Santa Barbara in triple overtime, 94-90.
article.headline: LSU wins first triple-overtime game in school history
article.linkText: LSU wins 3OT thriller against UC Santa Barbara
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- LSU coach Sue Gunter saw a lot more of
UC Santa Barbara than she wanted.

	   "I knew it was going to be a really, really good game,'' Gunter
said. "But I didn't know it was going to be quite that good.
They're an excellent team.''

	   Aiysha Smith's 3-pointer with 55 seconds left in the third
overtime, put No. 4 LSU ahead for good as the Tigers held off (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 20 AP) UC Santa Barbara 94-90 on Saturday in a game that was tied 16
times and had 14 lead changes.

	   "I was just hoping it would go in,'' said Smith, who missed her
first three long-range attempts. "It was a tough game. They're a tough team.''

	   The Gauchos cut the Tigers' lead to one at 89-88 on a 3-pointer
by Debbie Caine with 43 seconds to go, but LSU outscored them 5-2
the rest of the way.

	   The loss snapped UC Santa Barbara's (18-4) seven-game winning
streak. It was the fifth time in six games that LSU (22-1) faced a Top 20 opponent.

	   "I think we underestimated Santa-Barbara a little bit,'' Temeka
Johnson said. "They're good.''

	   Smith scored 30 points and grabbed 11 rebounds. Seimone Augustus
added 20 points for the Tigers, Johnson had 18 and Doneeka Hodges
10.

	   Kristen Mann led UC Santa Barbara with 27 points, Jess Hansen
had 23, and Lindsey Taylor and Mia Fisher each scored 13.

	   LSU had a 62-60 lead with 10 seconds left in regulation, but
Augustus' jumper from the top of the key bounced off the rim,
Fisher rebounded and Hansen scored to tie it at 62 as time ran out.
	   
In the first overtime, Santa-Barbara took a 68-66 lead on Mann's
layup with 1:01 remaining. LSU tied i  "It's a matter of heart,'' Mann said. "We always thought we could do it.''

	   LSU, third in the nation in field-goal percentage, shot 42
percent. Santa Barbara, which shot 61 percent in a 77-72 win at
Illinois on Thursday night, shot 43 percent.

	   The Gauchos outrebounded LSU 53-46, led by nine by the 6-foot-8
Taylor, who fouled out with 55 seconds left in regulation.

	   "That 6-8 kid keeps the ball a lot,'' Augustus said. "And her
teammates are right there when she tips it.''

	   The Tigers also struggled outside, making just 3-of-17 from
3-point range.

	   "We had hoped they would have a bad shooting game from outside
and 3-for-17 is exactly what we hoped for,'' UC Santa Barbara coach
Mark French said. "We wanted them to have a bad night shooting,
keep their penetrations down, and not turn the ball over much. It
was a sound philosophy, and we were right there.''
